\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces The two construct poles for a log with variants $\langle a,b\rangle $ and $\langle a,c\rangle $ over $\mathcal  {A}=\{a,b,c\}$. The trace model memorizes the variants and accepts nothing unseen; the flower model accepts everything, so a construct-pure metric must score it $1$ (its uselessness is a precision and simplicity verdict, not a generalization verdict).}}{8}{figure.1.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:poles}{{2}{8}{The two construct poles for a log with variants $\langle a,b\rangle $ and $\langle a,c\rangle $ over $\mathcal {A}=\{a,b,c\}$. The trace model memorizes the variants and accepts nothing unseen; the flower model accepts everything, so a construct-pure metric must score it $1$ (its uselessness is a precision and simplicity verdict, not a generalization verdict)}{figure.1.2}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces ShadowGen pipeline. From the variants of the event log $L$, N-gram statistics up to order $N$ feed a stochastic walker (Katz backoff; novelty probability $\ensuremath  {p_{\mathit  {unseen}}}$; termination probability $\ensuremath  {p_{\mathit  {end}}}$). Generated traces are deduplicated against $L$, so the shadow log $\ensuremath  {L_S}$ contains only unseen traces. The model $M$ under evaluation enters only at the replay step, which yields the metric: the graded score \ensuremath  {\mathit  {Gen}_{\mathit  {shadow}}}{}, averaged over $K$ draws. A strict acceptance reading of the same shadow log (\ensuremath  {\mathit  {Gen}_{\mathit  {accept}}}) exists as a validation diagnostic (Sect.\nobreakspace  {}\ref {sec:eval:accept}), not as part of the released metric.}}{8}{figure.1.3}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:pipeline}{{3}{8}{ShadowGen pipeline. From the variants of the event log $L$, N-gram statistics up to order $N$ feed a stochastic walker (Katz backoff; novelty probability $\punseen $; termination probability $\pend $). Generated traces are deduplicated against $L$, so the shadow log $\shlog $ contains only unseen traces. The model $M$ under evaluation enters only at the replay step, which yields the metric: the graded score \genshadow {}, averaged over $K$ draws. A strict acceptance reading of the same shadow log (\genaccept ) exists as a validation diagnostic (Sect.~\ref {sec:eval:accept}), not as part of the released metric}{figure.1.3}{}}
